](https://arxiv.org/html/2406.09056v1#bib.bib4)is a significant milestone in the field of natural language processing (NLP), driving a revolution in language models’ understanding and generation of human language[> 56
](https://arxiv.org/html/2406.09056v1#bib.bib56). From automatically completing text and chatbots to complex question answering and article generation, LLMs not only enhance the quality of text generation but are also capable of managing a wide range of text generation tasks. However, as LLMs increasingly empower various industries, they also reveal escalating challenges in information security, copyright, and ethics, particularly in their ability to produce text content whose authenticity is challenging to discern[> 9
](https://arxiv.org/html/2406.09056v1#bib.bib9).
Currently, there are numerous methods for detecting and identifying AI-generated texts. Given that human performance in distinguishing between texts generated by LLMs and those written by humans barely surpasses random guessing, research has significantly shifted towards automated detection methods. These methods aim to identify subtle cues that are typically imperceptible to humans. The existing artificial intelligence (AI) text detection methods can be divided into two categories based on their working principles[> 21
](https://arxiv.org/html/2406.09056v1#bib.bib21):metric-based methodsandmodel-based methods. Metric-based methods, such as GLTR[> 12
](https://arxiv.org/html/2406.09056v1#bib.bib12), primarily rely on quantitative statistical indicators to evaluate text characteristics, while model-based methods, like RoBERTa[> 22
